A Republican strategy to hinder Obama's re-election
Republican leaders justified their policy on the need to fight electoral fraud.
However, the Brennan Center considers the latter a myth and says voter fraud is less common in the United States than the number of people dying from lightning strikes.
In fact, Republican lawyers have found only 300 cases of voter fraud in the United States in 10 years.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will negatively affect the participation rate.
In that regard, these measures will partly undermine the American democratic system.
Contrary to what happens in Canada, American states are responsible for organizing federal elections in the United States.
And along the same lines, a majority of American governments enacted, starting in 2009, new laws that made it difficult to register or vote.
This phenomenon has spread after the November 2010 elections, which saw the increase of 675 new Republican representatives in 26 states.
As a result, 180 bills were introduced in the year 2011 to restrict the exercise of voting rights in 41 states.
New election laws require voters to submit an identity card with a photograph, in addition to a test of American citizenship.
On the other hand, these laws reduce periods of early voting, invalidate the right to register as an elector on the day of the ballot and withdraw their right to vote for citizens with criminal records.
Before the 2006 election, no American state required voters to submit a photo ID.
Indiana State was the first to demand it.
The U.S. Supreme Court upheld the constitutionality of Indiana's law in 2008.
That's why Republican authorities were quick to extend that practice to other states.
In recent years, these authorities have supported bills in 34 states to force voters to submit a photo ID.
It is important to bear in mind that, contrary to what is happening in Quebec, American citizens do not have a universal identity card, such as the Social Security card.
In fact, 11 percent of American citizens, or 21 million people of voting age, do not have any photo ID issued by a government agency in their state.
On the other hand, five million new voters in 2012 lack an identity card with these characteristics.
But often obtaining the required identity card costs more than $100.
Thus, the new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities and low-income people.
Indeed, 25 per cent African-Americans, 15 per cent of people earning less than $35,000 a year, 18 per cent of citizens over 65 and 20 per cent of voters between the ages of 18 and 29 do not have a photography identity card.
And there's more.
In many states, voters who vote for Democratic candidates the most cannot use the photo ID issued by their institution.
On the other hand, those same states authorize members of fishing or hunting clubs who usually vote Republican parties to use documents issued by such clubs.
Before 2004, no state required proof of citizenship to vote.
Arizona was the first state to file such a demand.
Since 2011, a dozen states have adopted laws requiring voters to prove they are American citizens.
These measures clearly seek to limit the Hispanic vote.
It seems that two out of three Hispanic voters support the Democratic party.
On the other hand, Republican lawmakers in 2011 supported certain laws that abolished voter registration on the same day of the vote in eight states.
In addition, they limited the right of individuals and groups to create a service to help voters who wanted to register.
These restrictions have consequences.
For example, in the 2004 general election, voter registration campaigns contributed to the registration of some 10 million citizens.
Actions since 2009 resulted in the registration rate of new voters falling in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican lawmakers passed legislation in five other states that favored reducing the voting period in advance.
For example, in the 2008 Florida election, 33 percent of voters who voted in advance were African Americans, while the latter represented only 13 percent of the state's voters.
In the case of Hispanics, the same thing happened.
These represent only 11% of voters, equivalent to 24% of citizens who vote in advance.
However, whites, who make up 76 per cent of the electorate,, accounted for only 46 per cent of citizens who vote in advance.
Of course, Democratic lawmakers and their supporters have fervently opposed the adoption of laws restricting voter registration.
In this regard, Democratic governors have blocked several bills.
The U.S. Attorney's Office intervened to suspend the most controversial laws.
In part, it was possible to limit the damage.
For example, only 16 of 34 states passed the law requiring the presentation of a photo ID.
However, it is undeniable that the new rules adopted will complicate the exercise of voting rights in 2012.
Democratic critics denounce the partisan nature of the laws that have been voted on, as it is clear that they intend to influence the 2012 results in key states.
A 2011 Brennan Center report shows that states that have passed such laws account for 171 of the 270 votes needed in the electoral college to win the presidency.
It is too early to say with certainty whether these electoral system legislative changes will have a significant impact on the results of the 2012 presidential election.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will negatively affect the participation rate.
In this sense, the measures will partly undermine the American democratic system.
