With bitcoin, all network nodes are both depository of accounting books, verifiers, currency issuers and buyers and sellers.
How does that network work?
Each transaction between two users is actually done between two e-mail addresses in the form of an email.
A user can choose a different address for each payment, thus ensuring anonymity.
A set of information linked to this transaction is signed electronically through a dual-key encryption system.
The network can thus verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Thanks to the content of the file, it is also possible to ensure that bitcoin changes are contained in the public accounts book, which is disseminated throughout the network.
The key milestone is to write that new transaction in that book.
This goes through the resolution of a mathematical challenge thrown at computers and the winner, a kind of temporary central banker, will have the privilege of adding that complementary line.
This is a phase of file cutting, that is, transforming a large file into a shorter and more unique numerical footprint.
Computers "cock" the new transaction and add a number before "twisting" the set.
The goal is to find the number that offers a particular print (more zeros at first).
Once that number is found, the other nodes easily verify that it's the good one.
The transaction is then indestructibly linked to the joint chain of other transactions; any modification would change the footprint.
If, to commit a fraud, a user wanted to pay twice with the same money very quickly (less than ten minutes), the network would only accept as valid one of the two transactions; the other would be orphaned, as both have different prints.
The computer that solves the challenge takes 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, that reward is split in two regularly, likely before the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is therefore limited to 21 million, but they are divisible to the hundred thousandth, leaving a wide margin.
The difficulty of this challenge is also revealed in every increase in the computing power.
The life of the network already has its ups and downs.
Websites offering services for Bitcoin have been attacked and bitcoins have been stolen in storage.
