It's a new double or nothing from President Mohammed Morsi.
While Egypt is more divided than ever about the constitutional declaration, which provisionally grants him full powers, he decided to play the whole for the whole.
He took everyone by surprise on Wednesday, when he announced that the Constituent Assembly would vote on its final text the next day.
Just a week ago, the head of State had given the Assembly two more months to complete its work.
And Egypt has been using a multi-modified provisional text for almost two years, which weakens institutional stability and leads to judicial mess.
This new initiative has only increased the fracture in the country.
For his opponents, the president perseveres in his "autocratic delirium" and continues to "betray his word" and "foot the right."
On the part of his supporters, it is ensured that this is a measure to put an end to the institutional and political crisis faster and to accelerate the transition process.
A referendum should be organised over the next 15 days.
A very short period of time that forces the Brothers to renounce their draft to explain the text, article by article, to the Egyptians.
For the president, it is also a way of recovering popular and democratic legitimacy while the controversial causes havoc throughout the country.
Mohammed Morsi seems convinced that Egyptians will vote in his favor, as he said in an interview with the American weekly Time.
Considering that this appeal has been voted very quickly, it contains an ultimatum for the Egyptian people: "either they vote for my text or I maintain the full powers," powers that will supposedly come to an end with the adoption of the Constitution.
It is in this strange environment in which 85 members of this Constituent Assembly, Islamist for the vast majority, voted on the text yesterday.
Most Liberals did not attend the call.
By mid-November, a little before the constitutional declaration, they had closed the door because they felt they could not assert their views.
Representatives of human rights, religious minorities and civil society did the same.
In order to achieve the necessary quorum, 11 people, surrogate members, were added yesterday morning to a hurry.
Some of them are very close to the Muslim Brothers.
As expected, the articles voted on have been unanimous.
On the other hand, it is graceful that one of the few discrepancies of the day has been expressed practically at the time of prayer, so much so that several members of the committee came to think that the clock of the Constituent Assembly was wrong.
The text, which was still being voted on yesterday afternoon, consists of 234 articles.
Article 2, object of all eyes, remains finally identical to that of the 1971 Constitution, which stipulated that "the principles of Sharia are the main source of law."
Salafist parties, for whom the establishment of Islamic law is a fundamental vindication, hoped that "principles" could be replaced by "the rules," which would have allowed for stricter application.
For Islamists, the fact that this article has not been modified is a guarantee of their goodwill and respect for the other components of Egyptian society.
Liberals call it hypocrisy and consider it to be nothing more than an advertising trick.
According to them, the Islamization of the Constitution is done through other articles.
They refer, in particular, to article 220, which gives the Al-Azhar University an advisory role, in particular for anyone who is to confirm its conformity with the Sharia law.
According to Egypt specialist Sophie Pommier, it is disturbing because "people called to pronounce themselves are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
Here we glimpse the premises of a theocracy."
Liberals' fears are also heightened by the fact that the university's next rector would be much less moderate than the current one.
"For now, there is no specific religious involvement.
With this Constitution we are within the framework of civil status.
Most of the jurists who have worked on this text are not ulemas but university students, some of them trained in the French system," explains Alexis Blouet, who prepares a thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
But he acknowledges that there may be some ambiguity around article 220, as the terms used imitate religious vocabulary.
"We refer in particular to the term iqh [Islamic jurisprudence, ndlr].
And the question that might arise in the future would be to what extent are the competent civil judges to rule over all this."
Beyond its religious character, the text voted yesterday received many criticisms that refer to the extended powers conferred on the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brothers will argue that there are few compared to those they were during the previous regime.
Another conflicting point: the powers conferred on the army.
In the military's wish, the review of the defence budget will not be submitted to Parliament, but to a national defence council.
Nor will the prosecution of civilians be prohibited in military courts, as requested by human rights associations.
These also showed their concerns about the text, which they consider libertarian.
The crime of blasphemy is maintained and, from now on, insults are prohibited, which could have serious consequences for freedom of expression, especially that of the press.
Moreover, no article emphasizes the protection of women, stresses Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
According to her, the only positive thing has been the prohibition of torture under article 36.
The word was not included in the previous Constitution.
