In November 1979, a group of the Islamist student demonstration occupied the American embassy in Tehran and took 52 graduates as hostages.
His release was to be in exchange for the dethroned shah Mohamed Réza Páhlevi, who after the revolution fled to the US, a country that had sponsored his regime for decades.
For the American administration, the situation offered no positive perspective: throwing the shah overboard could not allow it, since, if it did, it endangered the confidence of its allies in other countries.
But the release of the hostages in Iran, where the revolution had led to the constitution of the theocratic regime, was not within its reach.
It was a blow to the prestige of the United States, which subsequently intensified further with the failed attempt to forcibly release the hostages.
Prisoner diplomats were released 444 days after the Algerian government's negotiating intervention.
In the US, his fate caused a wave of solidarity and animation against Iran.
The failure in Iran contributed decisively to Jimmy Carter's defeat to Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential election.
The film "Argo" by director and actor Ben Affleck themed toot an episode of this story, which reaped a small success for America.
Shortly before the embassy was occupied, six employees escaped from the building.
After a complicated journey, they ended up at the residence of the Canadian embassy.
The CIA, in collaboration with the Canadian authorities, managed to get them out of Iran, for which he helped a covert story a stranger: they came out with Canadian passports, as members of the film team examining the location in the country for the shooting of a sci-fi superproduction.
Gender Combination
The plan outlined by "examining" expert Toni Mendez required Hollywood collaboration.
For the lie to seem truthful, the film project was written in specialized magazines, press conferences were organized, the fictional production society even had a royal office.
Details about the operation were kept secret for a long time, the film has been made from Tony Mendez's memories.
Affleck's film is a unique combination of several genres.
On the one hand, a realistic political thriller; on the other, a so-called "capermov," the story of an episode that went well, a deception (an example may be the Ocean's Eleven series).
The film combines moods. We found on the one hand well-documented sequences of Tehran. The sequence of credits shows emblematic photographs of the time of events, which were reflected in the same way in the film; there are not many differences in this regard.
On the other hand, typical Hollywood scenes a little lighter, marked by irony and a slight exaggeration.
And besides, scenes from the CIA plant and other institutions: men in suits who analyze the situation at the negotiating table, in the hallways of the office, by phone...
Ben Affleck has managed to restart his career in excellent fashion.
The actor, who had been mocked, has become a respectable director and his way of acting has ceased to be the target of ironic comments.
Argo is his third feature film, after "Goodbye Little, Goodbye" (2007) and the thriller "The Town. City of Thieves" (2010).
At the same time, it's Affleck's first film in which the action takes place in the city of Boston, where he grew up.
Likewise, the sensitivity of capturing the atmosphere of the place was a feature that placed the directors of old films above Hollywood standards.
And Affleck demonstrates this in Argo, where Tehran "whistles" in Canada.
The film's best scenes take place in the streets, in the reconstruction of the true events. The introductory sequence of the embassy's takeover is impressive for its synoptic capacity, which, at the same time, conveys the excitement of bewilderment and the lack of foresight that arises when, somewhere, the story takes a step forward.
Affleck and his collaborators get a similar effect on the fictional scenes (the impostor team in Tehran's bazaar).
Too much action in too many places
The director had to accept the fact that an explained story doesn't offer much in the cinematic sense of the most intriguing scenes.
And he manages pretty well. Sometimes it adds something to reality: here it doesn't all come out so elegantly (the scene in which the crisis at Tehran airport haunts, the diversion of a call to America and the unbridled search behind its clue turn into madness).
Argo's weakness is the lack of control that arises from the need to show too much action in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman have a very funny role as Hollywood collaborators, although their characters deserved more space and are by no means the only ones in this film.
For these reasons, Affleck's film loses a bit of dramatic stroke, but it's a film that can be followed with a moderate interest, valuing its realization and the retro style of a thriller that evokes the 1970s.
But if it collapses, that will be difficult.
As an evocation of a real story and as proof of how exaggerated the notions of omnipresence and omniscience of the secret services can be, it is enough.
