The architecture firm MVRDV shows that the real adventures are not only in the head - in the example of the Spijkenisse library and the recently completed "book mountain" - 2 photos
"I think the building is fun, it looks futuristic, and there's finally something interesting to see," says Lisette Verhaig, a passer-by who passes by the street.
And Stefan Spermon, an IT technician at a large company located near the library, points out: "In addition, the building is nice."
But I wonder why we need a library today.
We all have the internet, tablets and e-books.
Nobody comes in for like these old-fashioned libraries, doesn't they?
Spijkenisse, a bedroom city located at the gates of Rotterdam that barely deserves a fleeting visit, holds the dubious honour of having risen with a record to forget.
The population of 80,000 has the lowest literacy rate in the Netherlands.
To counter this embarrassing situation, a few years ago it was decided to contribute in some way to the general culture and copy the seven fictitious bridges that are represented on euro banknotes in the form of decorated reinforced concrete miniatures.
The success of the educational offensive was limited.
And that's how the policy makers decided that there was only one possibility to improve the statistics: a library had to be built.
Winy Maas, of the Dutch architecture studio MVRDV, a master in the art of bar diagrams and responsible for fun buildings at the same time as cynical, took the theme with her usual serenity and appeared at the presentation of the contest in 2003 with five books under her arm and a smile on her face.
And as the jury looked perplexed around him and shrugged his shoulders, Maas proceeded to stack the books by size forming a pyramid and concluded his brief speech with the following words: "Dear fellow citizens:
Here you have it, my proposal for the Spijkenisse Mountain of books, the so-called "Boekenberg.""
Nine years later, the 30-million-euro mountain rises in the planned place.
This is part of the revitalization project, which is completed with an underground parking, a supermarket, a post office and a couple of housing and townhouse buildings.
In early November, the Lies Mountain was awarded the second "Best Library of NL 2012" award.
In addition, the project is also nominated for the 2012 "Dutch National Wood Award."
In this way, the small city without history, which to date had nothing more to offer than a postmodern pedestrian area and an incredibly ugly town hall behind which white facade one would rather intuit a dairy plant, now has a work of contemporary architecture.
But above all, Spijkenisse now has the first public cultural building in its history.
The long way to the book
The first impression is that it is a book paradise under a cheesemaker.
It is true that there is an elevator that transports us right to the center of this mountain massif, but the true lovers of space and reading do not use it, but prefer to melt with their topography every step of climbing to the top.
The fully glazed interior is bright and easy to cover with the view, the brick floor and the elegant lanterns unequivocally support the public condition of the library.
The urban environment is perfect.
By raising the view you can visualize the park's banks, dogs and boys and girls playing football.
And everywhere books, books and more books.
"Normally the book shelves are arranged along the facade and in the middle opens a huge dark room that is usually somewhat uncomfortable and impersonal," says Winy Maas.
What we've done is turn the classic spatial configuration upside down and get the reading area out of the inside out.
The interior of the mountain is very well taken advantage of: in the middle are the offices, the Internet library, the chess club, the environmental education center and the maintenance room.
Special mention deserves the black shelves that assume the functions of wall covering, parapet and railing at the same time.
The sight, touch and smell are strange.
Even architects and civil engineers all the day shake their heads when they hear of this unknown material.
"We wanted to work with recycled materials," Joop Trouborst, project manager in the city of Spijkenisse, explains.
And that is how one day, on a frisian farm, we encounter the right by-product from agriculture.
For many years, plastic fabric of a small-largemum thick has been used in greenhouses and fields in the Netherlands as a base to hold the roots of crops.
This is a cheap and efficient material.
This fine tissue lasts two seasons and then discards.
For the library this fabric was presected, for the first time in such quantities, until it gets plates four centimeters thick.
With heat and pressure, the so-called agricultural plastic (KLP) changes color and becomes a dark, homogeneous and resistant material that smells like a mix of new car and sports shoe.
After 105 steps you reach the top of the mountain.
At the end of this continuous route of almost 500 meters around the mountain awaits us the reward: from the cafeteria you not only have a fantastic view of the city, but you can also enjoy tasty Dutch croquettes and its ficus planted in huge pots.
These create a pleasant environment at the same time that keeps the atmospheric humidity suitable for this mountain of literature.
Donations for a new soul
"Although it costs to believe it given its large glazed surfaces, this building is an exemplary project in terms of ecology," says Trouborst.
The necessary heating and cooling are obtained from geothermal energy.
Although the mountain of books is set under a huge glass pyramid, even on sunnier days the sunshine only shines for a few hours inside.
The huge wooden fences located in a transverse direction to the glass facade serve to shade and absorb most of the sun's rays.
This creates a comfortable inner climate.
The rest is a matter of automatic shutters.
Stefan Spermon, the skeptical IT worker, has already dared to set foot in the new library.
And Lisette Verhaig has been there, too.
Likewise, Chinese traditional medicine professor Cynthia Bogarde has visited the library. She describes the "Boekenberg" as Spijkenisse's "late soul."
The reason is that, on the occasion of the inauguration that took place a couple of weeks ago, all the inhabitants of the city were invited to donate a book from their private collection.
In this way it is intended to fill, for the moment, the optical holes of a library that does not yet have its complete archive; it currently has 70,000 copies.
The concept has gone deep.
The shelves are full.
"There's nothing worse than a half-empty library," says architect Winy Maas.
"I think thanks to our initiative now all the inhabitants have a certain link to this building.
Everyone knows his book is part of the library.
Even if he's just there to decorate.
In this way, the MVRDV study has achieved a success in this discipline that in specialized slang is known as "creation of an identity."
The city of Spijkenisse has written a piece of the history of literature.
Regardless of how young and uneducated it can be.
Finally a starting point to shape your identity.
