This was and remains open to interpretation and it seems that Islamists will take advantage of this vague formulation, as well as the room for legal maneuvering that entails, to impose a stricter interpretation of sharia law.
This is at least what a new added article suggests: in all sharia issues it is mandatory to consult Al-Ashar University, the country's most important Islamic institution with great power in all Sunni Islamism.
It doesn't have to be so, but this may mean that clergy would control the legislation, something that - in fact - would result in the incapacitation of the judiciary.
Much of the draft constitution is open to interpretation
What is also problematic is that it intends to maintain military jurisdiction.
During Mubarak's dictatorship, these courts served to exert a harsh repression of the opposition.
After the dictator's fall, up to 11,000 civilians were being held in military prisons.
As the draft establishes, the state must protect "the true essence of the Egyptian family" and "promote its morals and values."
This is such an imprecise formulation in legal terms that with the help of this article state institutions could even control the contents of cinematography and literature.
Speaking clearly, this is nothing but censorship.
Indeed, no article explicitly establishes equality between men and women.
Instead another bans the offending or slandering the Prophet Mohammed and his legacies.
However, it is unclear what an offense is and how it should be sanctioned.
Equally dubious is the formulation that bans "offensing people"
Is a cartoon of the president or a joke about a lawyer enough?
Question of interpretation, like many other things in the draft that has been presented to Mursi for signature and that, according to his words, "very soon" he will be presented to the Egyptians for a referendum.
"The revolution is back"
The opposition has been closing ranks for weeks over the superiority of Islamists.
