"We are not tired yet, the blood of our brothers has not yet been atoned," opposition politician Chaled Ali was quoted in the Egyptian media.
And several judges announced that they did not wish to supervise the referendum, so it would not be considered valid.
"The Koran is our constitution"
For its part, the well-organized Muslim community called for a counter-demonstration; just in case not in Tahrir Square, but after a prayer across the Nile, to Cairo University.
Many women covered in a veil and supporters of the Salafists took part in it to the cry of: "the people demand the application of the divine law."
They demanded that Mursi "clean up the country," while proclaiming: "The Koran is our constitution."
A struggle for the sovereignty of the symbolic Tahrir Square, where it all began, would have provoked a situation similar to that of a civil war.
Clearly, Mursi's supporters didn't want to risk something like this happening.
The Muslim brothers said that both those who oppose the draft constitution and its supporters would have expressed their views loud and clear.
Now the time would have come to let the people decide in the polls what direction the country should follow.
In this regard, it seems that the draft Islamists is guaranteed the majority.
"The expression 'Human Rights' doesn't even appear"
Hafez Abu Saeda is furious with this forced constitutional process that should actually have lasted until February and included all social forces.
This 48-year-old human rights lawyer and president of the Egyptian Human Rights Organization (EOHR) defended the Muslim brothers when they were being held in prison or had to face a trial during Mubarak's dictatorship.
Not because he shared his ideology, but because for him human rights are indivisible.
For this reason he was beaten, convicted and imprisoned.
"And now the expression "Human Rights" does not even appear in the new constitution," he laments in a conversation with the newspaper "Welt am Sonntag."
The extension of Mursi's powers to the three branches of state led this lawyer to resign.
The measures taken are flagrant violations of the rules of the democratic game and will lead Egypt to a new dictatorship.
"Instead of strengthening civil society, what the president has done is abolish it," Saeda laments.
However, democracy cannot function without civil society organizations.
Saeda feels abandoned, also by the international community, which observes the ideological struggle that is taking place on the banks of the Nile with a mixture of curiosity and tension.
This could turn against him.
A protester in Tahrir Square warns: "You are conceiving a monster you can't control."
The Norwegian rakfisk: the most smelly fish in the world?
Norway's five million people enjoy one of the highest living standards, not only in Europe but in the world.
Is it possible that the country's success has any bearing on its greed for a very smelly fish?
Take a series of overly cured cheeses.
Place them in the middle of a mountain of dirty, wet football clothes.
Leave it there for a week.
You can then smell the crippling aroma of rakfisk, one of Norway's delicacies.
I'm in the small town of Fagernes, about three hours from Oslo.
It's snowy. The scenery is spectacular and that smell, always present, floats in the air.
The rakfisk is salted trout that is allowed to ferment in water during, depending on how smelly you prefer it, up to a year.
As it gets dark and gets colder, the Norwegians flock to a festival that is held here in Fagernes, dedicated to this delicacy of the most, so to speak, captivating.
"You eat raw and then drink a glass of aquavit from a drink," says Havard Halvarsen, a city firefighter who is also known as the "General of Rakfisk," who is in charge of organizing the festival.
Everywhere we see people eating this fish that is stored in small cubes and drinking significant amounts of the drink.
"Some people like aquavit more than rakfisk," Havard says.
The drink can kill the smell.
I'm trying some bits.
If you can avoid passing it near the nose, not bad; it's not much different from a portion of sushi that has traveled a few kilometers by bus.
The rakfisk is a product that comes from a very different time, when poverty hit Norway and where, before refrigeration existed, fish was stored during the autumn submerged in water and salt in airtight barrels.
Later, in the middle of winter, when it is already well fermented, it is removed and, evidently with the inactive senses due to alcohol, it is eaten.
Just a generation ago, thousands of Norwegians were forced to leave their country in search of work, and emigrated mainly to the United States.
The population is now rising rapidly; more than 13 per cent are immigrants, attracted by abundance of jobs, high wages and a comprehensive social services system.
A stream of Sweden's inhabitants, the old rival and even not too richer than Norway, arrives in this country to work.
rakfisk is considered important, an essential, if quite smelly, part of Norway's past.
It is among the most expensive dishes to be bought.
But, in fact, it's all expensive. A beer cane or sandwich costs you the cool of 10 euros ($14) each.
Norway does not usually appear on the agenda of international news and most Norwegians like it to be.
Here people are still unwilling to pronounce the name of Anders Breivik, the far-right racist who shot and killed 77 people, including men, women and children.
Instead, they refer to the shooting as "the July 22 event."
Norwegians find it very hard to believe that in their peaceful country one of their own was able to commit such cruelty and murder.
After much of Norway's current wealth, there has been growth, from the early 1970s, of one of the world's largest oil and gas industries.
"But oil isn't the only reason we're doing so well," says Anna, our waitress, as she goes past rakfisk trays and who, with her long blonde mane and striking blue eyes, she represents the image of Norwegian welfare.
"We are, as you say, prudent people".
His English, like most people in this country, is impeccable.
"We don't like to brag, we don't like ostentation".
Norway has managed its oil wealth with great caution; everything except a small percentage of money from this industry is invested in a special fund for the benefit of future generations.
While everyone wasted money they didn't have during the years preceding the financial crisis around the world, Norway kept the wallet closed.
"As long as we can ski in winter and hike in summer, we're happy," Anna says.
"And eat rakfisk," he adds with a laughing crowd.
I'm in the snow queuing to eat something; I've had enough rakfisk.
Now a moose burger is certainly something different and quite succulent to taste.
But at night, that smelly fish comes back.
The hotel I stay in is one of the many venues where a rakfisk dinner is held where diners vote the best fish, or perhaps the one that tests the nostrils the most.
A television has connected live with a bird-carrying presenter who is surrounded by rakfisk dishes.
Looks like the Eurovision contest.
"What are your scores for the best fish up there in the mountains, Thor-Juergen?"
"Here's our score, Havard".
There's laughter and applause.
A man falls off the chair, perhaps beaten by the aquavit.
Or maybe it's the vapours of all that fish.
Mexico: Enrique Peña Nieto faces a tough start
